<h1>Compare SPA with MPA apps</h1>

<p>A Single-Page Application (SPA) is a web application that loads a single HTML page and dynamically updates the content as the user interacts with the app.</p>
<p>SPA don't require page refresh</p>
<p>MPA require server page load and full page refresh</p>
<p>SPA click then dynamically updates page with data</p>
<p>MPA click then new HTML page returned with data</p>

<h3>Main differences</h3>
<p>SPA: Asynchronous data transfer</p>
<p>MPA: Get all data then send to page</p>
<br>
<p>SPA: CSR JS in browser</p>
<p>MPA: SSR Code runs on server then html sent to browser</p>

<h3>SPA Advantages</h3>
<p>Better performance</p>
<p>Faster data load</p>
<p>Better UX because user flow not broken</p>

<h3>SPA Disadvantages</h3>
<p>SEO issues</p>
<p>Dynamic content hard to index for search engines</p>
<p>Initial load slower</p>

<h3>MPA Advantages</h3>
<p>Scalability</p>
<p>Each page self contained</p>
<p>Modular and easy to extend</p>

<h3>MPA Disadvantages</h3>
<p>SSR can be hard on server during high traffic</p>
<p>This can increase cost</p>
<p>Slower performance</p>

<h3>Choosing</h3>
<p>SPA: UX driven application and real-time data like live statistics</p>
<p>MPA: content-driven website like blogs or newsletter</p>
